Students of Color at UW
Went to the internet to learn about Islam and found "literally the worst stuff"

Umar struggles with the in-between identity experience, where one realizes what the family has left behind in their home country and has trouble reconciling how to bridge the two. --> Update: I resonate with Umar's experience in the sense that prior to having the opportunity to visit my family's hometown in Mexico I did not understand what led them to migrate to the U.S. Much like Umar, I also feel an obligation to take advantage of the privileges my parents/ family members were not/are not afforded in Mexico.

Awais receives support he did not expect post 9/11.  --> Update: People should listen to this story because it is not too common that people of color receive support from what might be considered rural white Americans that are not as exposed to communities of color.

People show solidarity, although the way people do this (in this instance) makes Mouna uncomfortable and yet thankful for allies.  --> Update: This is important to hear because white allies felt pity that Trump was elected, when in reality our lives (most POC) have been more or less dictated by instances of discrimination and racism prior to Trump. This is normal to us, although Trump's election did increase fear.
Finding community as a person of color in Madison is hard at first.
Representation matters.  People want to participate in local politics and yet they are unable because of city boundaries.
It takes more than having good intentions to create transformational change.

Educators single out students for being culturally unique. Here, good intentions are invasive although Mouna uses this opportunity to share her love for Islam.  --> Update: This is important to hear because in spaces that are primarily white people of color may stand out, in this case Mouna was unique.  When students of color are unique they are often singled out and it can often make us feel uncomfortable.

Well-intentioned white people could learn how to truly engage in these practices by inviting black and brown people to lead them along the process.  --> Update: This is important to hear because it often feels that some well-intentioned white individuals "know" what is best for our communities/us without really understanding how complex our realities are.
There is a need for representative leadership and leaders who will push the boundaries for transformational change in the city.

It is still hard to talk about trauma in communities of color.  --> Update:  This is an important point because it is not common to talk about trauma in communities of color and it varies across ethno-racial groups.

Sometimes all "troubled youth" need is someone to lend them an ear without judgement as opposed to being targeted for their behavior. --> Update: People should listen to this because students understand how the masses (in this case teachers) can misinterpret their behavior without understanding that sometimes these youth have no one else that cares about them.  This was common for peers I had growing up in an inner city school.

There is an urgent need to treat students with trauma in our schools.  --> Update:  People should listen to this because it is sometimes assumed that trauma follows a one-size-fits-all model when it comes to students of diverse backgrounds and it does not.

There is a need for diverse mental health professionals that hold similar identities to those seeking therapy. People want to talk about what bothers them directly without having to explain how their identity matters.
The burden of teaching professors how to be culturally sensitive falls on the shoulders of students of color at UW.  Course design and framing are important.
Decision-making at institutions of higher education should be representative and culturally sensitive.

Students of color at PWI's constantly have to go through additional emotional labor because they become representatives of their communities on campus. --> Update:  This is important to hear because we're tired of having to go through the additional labor of ensuring our professors understand us.  The burden should not always fall on our shoulders, especially in a city/university that prides itself on diversity.

UW course did not equally conceptualize white domestic terrorists.  --> Update: This is important to hear because the people depicted as domestic terrorists are not the white men committing these atrocities.
Wants to see underrepresented people in positions of power.
Great story. I chose to highlight this because I think it is important to show strength-based perspectives. This also emphasizes the importance of community support

Really highlights Madison segregation. Southside is predominately racial minorities and the West side is really white. Just driving around the city you can tell who lives where because of how the city takes care of the different areas.
